Screaming to the world
The marketing campaign Looks Like You Need Iceland seems to have gotten off to a good start and the cries and calls out in nature are starting to attract people all over the world.
“You have the answer, I need Iceland,” says a woman in the big world in comments to an ad from the Looks Like You Need Iceland marketing campaign on YouTube.
Another spectator says he will keep Iceland in his heart forever and a young woman says she has to get to Iceland as soon as possible because her boyfriend lives there.
Unfortunately, she is in the United States and expects to have to wait a few more months.
Another viewer asks if the walk to Iceland is possible, because there are no planes.
It is not known if he came from another time zone.
Egill Þórðarson of Peel advertising agency, which produced the ads together with international advertising agency M&C Saatchi, says the response has exceeded expectations.
“I’ve been involved in many Inspired By Iceland campaigns that have been very successful, but this new campaign is already beating records.
Basically, this is about creating PR value, that is, getting foreign media to cover the campaign, and it has gone incredibly well.
In a relatively short period of time, we have received coverage in about 700 media outlets around the world, reaching more than two billion people.
The value of that coverage is priced at ISK 1.8 billion.
It’s not bad.”
The main market is usually the United States, and the campaign has gone very well there, although Americans are not on their way to Iceland in the near future.
According to Egill, well-known markets such as Denmark, the UK and Germany have also recovered well, as has Russia, which is a pleasant surprise.
There were also reactions from foreign regions, such as India, which were not expected.
“These ads have travelled farther than we expected,” says Egill, and it should be noted that over four million people have watched the content on YouTube.
“We couldn’t have asked for a better start.”
The photos on this opening were taken by Árni Sæberg, photographer of the newspaper Morgunblaðið, during the shooting of advertisements entitled “Let It Out” in the middle of last month.
The film was shot on locations such as the Skólavörðustígur in Reykjavik, Reynisfjörður, Skógarfoss, Sólheimajökull and in a cave at Hjörleifshöfði.
The film was directed by Samúel Bjarki Pétursson and Gunnar Páll Ólafsson at Skoti productions and shot by Óttar Guðnason.
The film stars Anna Jia from Iceland and Murphy Cardenas from Cuba and Hungary.
Dozens of Icelanders participated in the production of the advertisements, but at the same time as recordings were taking place in Southern Iceland, another group was in Western Iceland and the West Fjords.
According to Egill, “Let It Out” is only the first part of the Looks Like You Need Iceland campaign, but a winter campaign is planned in collaboration with M&C Saatchi.
“This is just the first phase of this work for Íslandsstofa,” says Egill, adding that the collaboration with M&C Saatchi has gone extremely well.
“It’s great to work with them.
In projects like this, it is very important to have foreign partners with knowledge of the markets we are talking to.”
