Bought a boat after tenth grade
“I don’t think there are many sailors working in the country’s kindergartens,” says Axel Örn Guðmundsson, who fishes in the summer and studies psychology at the University of Iceland in the winter.
Coastal fishing is a very comfortable summer job when you are studying.
If you fish well, you can have a good income and I think it’s great to be able to avoid taking a student loan.
The income is also good enough for the winter,” says Axel Örn Guðmundsson, a 25-year-old student of psychology, who is fishing this summer as he has in previous summers.
Axel had just moored in Tálknafjörður when a journalist reached out to him late in the evening at the beginning of the week.”
“In the winter when I was in the tenth grade, I took the boatmaster’s certificate for boats under twelve metres in length, and I bought my boat the summer after I finished primary school.
I have been fishing on my own boat every summer since.
I bought the boat used from my friend, Hartmann Jónsson, and I named the boat after him.
Hartmann had grown up when I bought the boat and stopped sailing and he was very happy when he saw that the boat was named after him.
Hartmann died a few years after I took over the boat,” says Axel, adding that he bought the boat for three million.
“I made an agreement with Hartmann to pay half, one and a half million, at the beginning of the summer and the other half at the end of the summer when I had finished fishing.
So I had the boat debt-free at the end of my first summer on it.”
But how could a boy have one and a half million to pay for a boat when he had just finished elementary school?
“I had already made a deposit and saved money, I had been working with my father at sea when I was a boy, I was fishing with him every summer and got my share.
I also put my baptismal money in my boat fund.”
Axel was born in Ísafjörður, where all his maternal relatives are from, but he has lived in Kópavogur since he was a boy.
“I am allowed to fish here in the western area because I have a legal residence with my grandmother in Ísafjörður.
I learned about these areas here in the west from paddling with my dad.
I move between fjords depending on how I feel, because this fishing area covers the entire Westfjords.
Although I prefer to be in the west, I have also fished around Snæfellsnes and elsewhere.
I have also fished in the south, but mostly for grayling," says Axel, who always rowes alone early in the morning and says he sometimes talks to the gulls and sings to the sky, while being alone for hours on end out on the sea.
“The internet connection at sea is good, so I can make calls, listen to podcasts and music.
I don't mind being alone on a boat.
Of course, I try to avoid getting into trouble, but there have certainly been occasions when the weather has been bad, but there has never been much danger,” says Axel, who is lucky that he is never seasick.
He says the length of the working day depends on how the fishing is going.
“In coastal fishing, I am never fishing for more than 14 hours at a time, but I have also been fishing in other systems, for example in the rental quota, but then I have been continuously for one and a half days out at sea fishing.”
He says that the arrangements for coastal fishing allow him to catch 770 kilograms a day, which he finds inhibiting.
“Other restrictions are that I am not allowed to fish on Fridays, Saturdays and Sundays, and I am only allowed to fish twelve days a month, during the four months of coastal fishing, in May, June, July and August.
In my opinion, fishermen should choose their fishing days according to the weather and nothing else.
This unnecessary pressure is placed on people to calm down instead of having 48 days over the whole summer and being able to choose as they see fit.
For my part, I would also like to see a division into zones, and sea areas that are well located near fishing grounds should be able to benefit from this,” says Axel, who mainly catches cod from salt water in his coastal fisheries, but only haddock and a few other species float along.
Axel works during the winter with his university studies at the kindergarten Núpi in Kópavogur.
“I don’t think there are many sailors working in the country’s kindergartens,” says Axel proudly, adding that he only intended to work temporarily at the kindergarten.
“I got stuck there because I think it’s a great job.
I hope that my psychology studies will be useful to me at the preschool level in the future,” says Axel, who is also well advanced in his business studies.
Registration error prevented re-entry surveillance
An error in the registration form that people fill out when they arrive in the country meant that a person, resident in Iceland, was not called back for testing.
It is not required to enter a personal identification number if the person fills out the form in English, as is the case when it is done in Icelandic.
"This will be examined this week," says a specialist at the Department of Public Health.
Three domestic infections were detected at the Department of Virology yesterday.
One of the persons who tested positive came to Iceland on 15 July, two days after the so-called re-entry quarantine rules came into effect.
Those who resided in Iceland are then screened upon arrival in the country and invited again for testing four to five days later.
In the afternoon news on RÚV, however, it was reported that the person concerned had followed the old system.
The sample taken at the border was negative and he was not called back to be tested for the virus.
Kamilla Rut Sigfúsdóttir, a specialist at the Department of Public Health, says in an interview with the news agency that this can be attributed to an error in the electronic registration form.
If people fill out the registration form in English, they are not required to enter a personal identification number, as is the case in the Icelandic version.
After all, it was primarily intended for foreign tourists.
Therefore, the person concerned did not receive an automatic invitation to come for testing.
Kamilla says that many people have followed the rules regarding re-entry quarantine even though they filled out the registration form in English, and in some cases, employers have also been vigilant about sending people for testing again after they arrived in the country.
"This will be examined this week how to make it easier for people to access this to raise awareness of the process."
The man is in isolation and six have been placed in quarantine.
They will all be tested, but two of them have started to show symptoms.
Tracing is now ongoing for the three cases that were detected yesterday, but it is largely completed for the two cases that were reported on Friday.
In both cases, sequencing by Icelandic Genomics has revealed that these are variants of the coronavirus that have not been detected in Iceland before.
In the second case, the links have been directed to Israel, although it is known that the person who brought the virus into the country had also travelled to other European countries.
Kamilla says it should be known tomorrow where the other virus was coming from.
A total of 15 are now in isolation according to the website COVID.is.
135 are in quarantine.
Four out of five cases unrelated
Five domestic infections have been detected in Iceland in recent days.
Of these, four are completely unrelated and, for example, the source of the infection that occurred at the Rey Cup sports tournament yesterday has not been found.
Tracing is still ongoing.
Originally, about thirty individuals were sent to quarantine, but they were reduced to sixteen.
In total, 34 people are in quarantine due to these new infections that were detected yesterday.
This is the second time in a short time that an infection has been detected at a sporting event and it has raised questions about whether such events should be held.
Jóhann K. Jóhannsson, head of communications at the Public Safety Department of the Icelandic National Police, says that is possible, as long as people follow the guidelines and rules.
“We are constantly urging all those who live here that it is necessary to maintain individual infection prevention.
We also need to make it clear to people who are holding events that there are certain rules in place that need to be followed.
Then you can hold events,” says Jóhann.
He says it is possible to prevent infection by maintaining individual infection prevention.
In addition, the rules and standards are under constant review.
“What needs to be done, and what the Department of Public Health and the National Institute of Health are constantly urging people to do, is to consider these individual infection prevention measures.
Both at home and at service companies.
That people wash their hands and use alcohol.
This prevents the spread of the infection,” says Jóhann.
“We need to urge people to continue on the good path we were on, in order to be able to maintain the success we have achieved so far.”
40% of COVID-19 victims had diabetes 2
Devon Brumfield heard on the phone how hard her father was struggling to catch his breath.
Her father had diabetes, and she urged him to seek medical help.
He died the next day.
The death was attributed to sudden respiratory distress due to coronavirus infection.
Diabetes was listed on the death certificate as the underlying cause, and Brumfield, who also has diabetes, is terrified that something similar will happen to her.
Reuters says Brumfield's fears are not unfounded.
Figures from a new study commissioned by the US authorities show that almost 40% of those who died had diabetes 2 as an underlying disease.
When the proportion of those who had not reached the age of 65 is examined, the proportion rises to half.
The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) study included more than 10,000 people in 15 states who died from the coronavirus between February and May.
Jonathan Wortham, a specialist in infectious diseases at the CDC, says the results are shocking, not least for those diagnosed with diabetes 2 and their loved ones.
Reuters commissioned a survey and the answers from the 12 states that responded point to similar rates.
10 states, including California, Arizona and Columbia, have not yet started reporting underlying diseases.
“Diabetes was already a slowly growing epidemic.
Now COVID-19 has broken through like a powerful wave,” Reuters quoted Elbert Huang, director of the Center for Chronic Disease Research and Policy at the University of Chicago.
Diabetes is more common among blacks and people of South American descent, who have also suffered worse from the coronavirus.
One of the best defenses for those with diabetes 2 is to keep the disease under control with exercise, a healthy diet and the help of a healthcare professional.
However, the coronavirus pandemic has made it difficult for many to maintain a routine.
Furthermore, the high cost of insulin has forced some to continue to attend work and thus risk being exposed to the virus.
Reuters points out that the US authorities may have been aware of the danger that those with diabetes 2 could be posed by the virus.
During the SARS coronavirus outbreak in 2003, more than 20% of them had the disease, and during the swine flu outbreak in 2009, this group was three times more likely to be hospitalised.
When MERS broke out in 2012, one study found that 60% of those who died or were admitted to intensive care had diabetes.
Charles S. Dela Cruz, a researcher at Yale University, says that because the impact of the COVID-19 virus could last longer, the pandemic has revealed a number of previously unknown complications.
“I’m afraid we’re going to see a tidal wave of problems once this is over,” says Andrew Bolton, president of the International Diabetes Federation.
Doctors have warned that the coronavirus pandemic may indirectly lead to an increase in diabetes-related complications, including kidney disease and kidney failure.
As well, new research suggests that the coronavirus may lead to an increase in cases of diabetes.
Reuters says scientists are trying to understand the link between the coronavirus and diabetes 2.
The virus attacks the heart, lungs and kidneys, organs that are already weakened in many people with diabetes.
In addition, a high ratio of glucose and lipids in diabetics can cause a veritable “cytokine storm”, as it is called when the immune system reacts too hard and attacks the body.
Damaged endothelial cells can also lead to inflammation, which in turn can cause fatal blood clots.
“It’s all one big puzzle,” says Dela Cruz.
“It’s all connected.”
The news has been corrected.
“We were offered champagne, then they left the room”
The couple Ásrún Magnúsdóttir and Atli Bollason accepted the unusual request from the artist Ragnar Kjartansson to have sex in front of a camera for a work that the artist was installing in Paris.
“We loved each other, so it wasn’t complicated.”
Atli Bollason never forgets when he met his wife and mother, Ásrún Magnúsdóttir, for the first time.
“I was very fascinated by it.
It was of course just the radiance, but I also thought she was incredibly cute.
And it still is,” he says.
Ásrún remembers this too, as her husband regularly recalls the first meeting.
“I’m hearing this story all the time.
Last time just this weekend,” says she, who was also attracted to her husband at first sight.
“I felt and still feel a lot of excitement around Atli, which I like.
There’s a lot going on and a lot happening, and I was fascinated by it.”
Atli says that the couple has emphasized in their relationship to go their own way.
“We do not tie our sacks with the same knots as our fellow travelers.
We avoid the routines that we see around us.”
That is probably why they welcomed the invitation from the artist Ragnar Kjartansson, although it was unusual to say the least.
“Our mutual friend Kristin Anna contacted us and asked if we could come to eat dessert with her, Ragnar and Ingibjörg, Ragnar’s wife, at Snaps.”
They accepted the invitation, met the trio at Snaps and had dessert wine and each their own dessert.
They listened to Ragnar, who guided them through his plans for an art exhibition at the Palais de Tokyo in Paris that autumn.
“He had a multidisciplinary video work called Scenes from western culture.
He described it in a simple way.”
Ásrún says that he described the work as banal and decadent scenes from everyday Western life.
“He had sketches of all the scenes he was going to shoot, and last he told us about what he wanted to know if we were interested in taking part in.”
The scene that Ragnar asked the couple to take part in was supposed to show a young middle-class couple making love in a minimalist room.
“This is intercourse with a beginning and an end,” says Atli.
The couple didn’t know Ragnar very well, although they knew him and he knew them, “but they knew us and thought we would fit in.
They said that they did not want to advertise for people.
Maybe they thought they wouldn’t get the right people, but people who would get sexually aroused from performing for others.”
They said goodbye to Ragnar and agreed to think about the matter, but it did not take long.
“When we ran out of Snaps, we said, ‘Why don’t we just do this?
It was just the way it was.
I trust Ragnar as an artist and his entire team,” says Ásrún and Atli agrees.
“It’s all about love and closeness”
The scene was shot in a nice apartment on Myra Street.
There was a very small film crew; the cameraman, Ragnar, the sound engineer and the couple.
After the tape was turned on, everyone left the room to wait outside in a car except Atli and Ásrún.
“We hadn’t decided how we were going to be.
We were given some brief instructions, but we tried to forget the time and place.
Being unaware of what we were doing and for whom.
We didn’t act, we just loved each other, so it wasn’t complicated,” says Ásrún.
But was it romantic?
“Yes, it was a bit romantic,” says Atli, and Ásrún agrees.
“We were offered champagne before they left the room.
It was a bit like being on holiday in a fancy hotel in Paris.”
The team was pleased with the couple’s performance, which moved them.
“When Tommi the cameraman watched it, he cried, he thought it was so beautiful,” says Atli.
“It’s as much about love and intimacy as it is about intercourse,” says Ásrún.
The couple’s parents have seen the work and Atli says that his mother heard the voice in his son at the Reykjavík Art Museum and then realized that he was part of the work.
“Then she turns around and starts to think about it,” says Atli.
“My mom and dad saw it in Paris.
We hadn’t told anyone about it in that way, but then my dad just sent me a message and said: Nice to come across the little family at the Palais de Tokyo,” recalls Ásrún.
And did the participation in the play deepen the relationship between Ásrún and Atli?
“At least we’re still together, so maybe it deepened something.
At least it deepened my relationship with my in-laws,” says Ásrún, laughing.
Ásrún herself saw the work in Copenhagen with a colleague.
“It was a little hard for me to be with someone else instead of you,” she says, turning to her husband.
“But it was nice to see this because it’s just one scene in a much larger work and when you saw it with the other works, it’s really cool.
I was able to tear myself away from this and was just proud.
And there was the little bean in my stomach,” says Ásrún, who was pregnant with the couple’s second child when the scene was shot.
“It was just beautiful.”
Anna Marsibil Clausen talked to Ásrún and Atli in Ástarsögur on Rás 1.
