Gerður’s mosaic works finally get to enjoy themselves to the fullest
In front of the Customs House in Reykjavík there is a large and deep hole.
On top of it are men with orange helmets.
There is also a large grave.
And more smaller machines.
The street is closed to traffic.
But the pavement is good, and many people now stop and admire the artwork made of millions of mosaic tiles — as if they had never seen it before.
Maybe they've never seen it before.
At least not seen it for themselves.
The work has so far been somewhat hidden, directly in front of it were parking lots that were always occupied.
People parked there, locked their cars in a hurry and then jumped off to do their errands in the city center.
“Vibrant and diverse public spaces” and “attractive urban character” are the guiding principles for the ongoing redevelopment of Tryggvagötu.
The aim is to beautify the area and allow Gerður Helgadóttir’s mosaic work at the Tollhús to enjoy a better view.
In front of the work there will be a square and since the area is well exposed to the sun, it is considered to be well suited as a rest area for pedestrians.
The artwork will be illuminated and the material will now be able to enjoy itself better than before on this 142-square-meter surface.
There will also be small “fog sprayers”, a kind of water sculptures, which offer play and give the area a certain mystery.
In this way, the improvements are described by the City of Reykjavík, which is carrying out the works together with Veitur.
The water supply, heating and electricity lines will be renewed.
Many of them are old, but the sewer and cold water lines are from 1925 and have therefore served residents and businesses in the city centre for almost a century.
When the street is reopened after the works, cars will be able to use it again.
However, it will be a one-way street, creating a quieter and more accessible space for pedestrians.
According to information about the Tollhúsið on the website of the Director of Customs, the building was taken into use in 1971 and its architect was Gísli Halldórsson.
Because the harbour shed extended through the house, there was a 250 square metre windowless wall area facing the street.
The building committee and the architect agreed that such a surface would have a negative effect on the overall streetscape, unless special measures were taken to enhance the appearance of the building.
The parties therefore agreed to have a permanent artwork installed there.
During this time, Gerður Helgadóttir, an artist, was widely spoken of, says the summary.
She had worked extensively on mosaic works in Germany and elsewhere.
It was decided to contact her first before deciding whether to hold a competition for the work.
It had often been discussed that the work had to reflect life at the harbour, as the harbour had been Reykjavík’s lifeline since it was built.
When the artist was interviewed, she was instantly captivated by such a work.
It was agreed that she would receive drawings and other assistance before leaving the country, where she would work on the proposals abroad.
Gerður was given the time she decided she needed, and when she returned home she put forward some proposals for discussion.
It was immediately agreed to ask her to do the work.
At the same time, Gerður was asked to sign an overall contract with the famous art company in Germany, the Oidtmann Brothers, with whom Gerður had worked for a long time on the installation of famous artworks throughout Europe.
Negotiations succeeded and Gerður worked on the installation of the artwork in the workshop of the brothers, who then took care of the installation at Tollhúsið.
The whole work was done exceptionally well, both by Gerður Helgadóttir and the Oidtmann brothers, says the summary.
It has since withstood the harsh Icelandic weather.
It took Gerður about two years to complete the work, which was finished and installed in 1972 and 1973.
The artist died two years after Tollhúsið was finished, aged only 47.
