Pension funds and long shadows
2019 was an important anniversary year in the history of pension funds in Iceland.
Civil servants had received pensions from the King of Denmark since the 19th century, but in 1919 a pension fund for civil servants was established, which eventually became a pension fund for all public employees.
The basis for the current pension funds for ordinary wage earners was laid by collective labour agreements in 1969, which provided for compulsory membership and full funded employment-related pension funds from the beginning of 1970.
In 1974, a law was passed on the basis of these agreements and the pension system continued to strengthen after that.
The wage-earner pension system was not the only radical change that the 20th-century labour movement forced through its wage struggles.
Unemployment insurance had been obtained in a similar way in the historic strikes of 1955, and the unions also gradually achieved their demands for sick leave and health insurance, substantial holiday entitlements, shortened working hours, housing reforms and other matters of great importance.
All these rights cost a great and tough struggle but proved, in retrospect, to be a much greater and more lasting improvement than the increase in the number of aurar in the salary envelope, which disappeared as hard as it did in the high of inflation that characterized the post-war period and until 1990 as many remember.
The process leading up to the establishment of general pension funds in 1969 was both long and complex.
Although it was eventually agreed that the funds would in practice be owned by their members, the labour movement had to agree that their boards should be appointed with equal representation of employers and members.
In the years following the establishment of the funds, the demand for a majority of workers in the boards of the funds was frequently discussed in the unions of wage earners, but it was never implemented, and therefore we still sit with the abnormal arrangement that representatives of the fund members are not in the majority in the boards of the funds.
Article 36 of Act No. 129/1997 on compulsory insurance of pension rights and the activities of pension funds deals with the investment policy of the funds.
Paragraph 1 states that “a pension fund shall be guided by the interests of its members.”
Paragraph 5 also states: “A pension fund shall establish ethical standards for its investments.”
The shareholder policy of the Merchants’ Pension Fund contains, among other things, the following provisions, in continuation of the aforementioned statutory provisions:
The Pension Fund is a member of the United Nations Principles for Responsible Investment (UN PRI), along with many of the largest pension funds and professional investors overseas and in Europe.
The guidelines discuss how a focus on environmental and social issues as well as good corporate governance can contribute to improved investment performance of portfolios.
Thus, the interests of investors and the goals of society in a broader context come together.
LV believes it is important that companies, especially those listed on the stock market, establish public policies on: good governance working conditions social responsibility and environmental issues.
The pension fund Gildi, which is one of the largest pension funds in the country, has adopted a “policy on responsible investment” with similar provisions.
This is all recalled here as an introduction to the latest buzzword in Icelandic, “shadow management”.
Since the word is new in the language, it is unlikely that it has been fully defined, but it seems to me that the following definition is now "most taken": Shadow management is when a leader of a trade union says in the media that he intends to send the representatives of the union on the board of a pension fund recommendations or instructions on how they should take a position on a particular issue.
If they do not follow the recommendations, they will be removed from the board at the earliest opportunity.
If the leader does not take this to the media and does not talk about dismissal, then it is not "shadow management" because such communications between people are of course always in the financial world as elsewhere.
I leave it to the reader to ponder which way he finds “shady.”
There are two men in particular who have tried to formulate this definition at the time of writing, on the morning of Saturday, July 25, 2020.
They are Hörður Ægisson, journalist at Fréttablaðið, and Ásgeir Jónsson, Governor of the Central Bank.
The issue for both of them arose after Bogi Nils Bogason, CEO of Icelandair, announced his intention to terminate the company’s contracts with flight attendants and stewardesses, and Ragnar Þór Ingólfsson, chairman of the Reykjavík Chamber of Commerce, issued a recommendation to its representatives on the board of the Icelandic Chamber of Commerce Pension Fund not to support the fund’s possible purchase of shares in the company, otherwise they could be forced to resign.
Shortly thereafter, Bogi Nils withdrew his decision and Ragnar Þór followed suit with his recommendations, which were of course based on Bogi Nils’s decision.
Nevertheless, Hörður and Ásgeir saw a reason to comment on the issue in the Friday edition of Fréttablaðið with big words about shadow governance, violation of the law and the urgent need for amendments to the law.
There, a small mound was indeed to carry a heavy burden, although the blessed mound had been in conjunction and had also been wiped out quickly.
Since the matter is important, let us consider the subject itself at the end.
I have previously described the relevant provisions of the Pension Funds Act.
These include that fund boards must safeguard the interests of fund members and have ethical standards in investments, and these points are elaborated in more detail in the articles of association of both Gildi and the Pension Fund of the Merchants, as I mentioned.
However, pension funds should NOT focus solely on short-term profitability in their investments.
Such a policy would be extremely dangerous, and we do not need to look far in the past to find examples of it, where large loans from banks and funds have gone to unethical adventurers and environmentalists, with disastrous consequences.
The CEO of Icelandair was obviously on slippery ice when he thought of wiping out an entire group of employees, thereby significantly reducing the goodwill that the company has enjoyed in the Icelandic market and weakening its position vis-à-vis investors.
Fortunately, he saw it and took it back.
Time will tell whether this is sufficient to ensure that the investment of pension funds in the company can be considered responsible towards the fund members in the end.
