Fearing a second wave of the pandemic
The Spanish government is currently struggling to contain the spread of COVID-19 in the country.
Spanish health authorities reported over 920 new cases of COVID—19, both on Thursday and Friday.
This is the highest number of new cases in a single day since the beginning of May, and the news comes as Spain begins to lift one of the strictest curfews in Europe.
The setback led to the UK authorities now requiring passengers arriving from Spain to quarantine upon return.
A week earlier, Spain was on the British list of safe countries.
The situation is worst in Catalonia in northeastern Spain, where the authorities have introduced more restrictions to try to stem the growth.
In the capital, Barcelona, entertainment venues will be closed for the next two weeks and retirement homes will have to close at midnight.
In addition, a curfew is now in effect for 200,000 residents in the Segria county in western Catalonia.
It is believed that the British decision will have a negative impact on the Spanish economy, which relies heavily on the arrival of foreign tourists and is badly affected by the pandemic.
Tui, the UK’s largest tour operator, cancelled all flights scheduled for today to Spain and the Canary Islands.
Governments around the world are said to be preparing for a second wave of the pandemic, but there seems to be little interest in reverting to the extensive curfews that have ruined economies.
For example, Boris Johnson, the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, has taken it very badly and compared it to a nuclear weapon that he does not want to use.
French Prime Minister Jean Castex said the nation “would not survive, economically or socially,” if a nationwide curfew were to be re-introduced.
Many officials are hoping that local measures that reach the inhabitants of individual towns, cities or regions will be enough to contain the virus in the next round if it comes.
