Entire apartment building rots down in the best location in the city
Romanian workers live free at Dunhaga 18-20.
In the meantime, the owners are applying for a building permit for renovations, but their application has been hovering in the system for almost three years.
In one of the oldest, greenest and most expensive neighbourhoods of Reykjavík stands a large three-storey apartment building.
On the ground floor of the building is about 600 square meters of retail space.
Behind the house are the doors of two staircases, each containing four rather spacious apartments.
They range in size from 93 to 130 square meters, most of them over 100.
The house has a lot of history.
It was built in 1959 and has hosted a video rental, a shoe shop, a dairy store, a gunsmith, a fish shop and most recently a university print shop.
The house has, to say the least, lost its beauty.
The house is now under severe damage, as can be seen in the attached pictures.
The owner of the house is D18 ehf.
According to the company register, the owners of D18 ehf. are, among others, Magnús Magnússon and Guðrún Helga Lárusdóttir.
Magnús led the owners’ group of Borgun and was the managing director of the holding company Borgun.
Among the owners of the holding company Borgun is Stálskip ehf.
Stálskip ehf. is an investment company owned by Guðrún Helga Lárusdóttir and her children.
Guðrún also owns a one-third stake in D18 ehf.
Guðrún and her husband, Ágúst Guðmundur Sigurðsson, once ran the shipyard Stálskip.
D18 ehf. bought the house in the summer of 2009 and has therefore had little or no maintenance since then.
Neighbors say that the condition of the house has deteriorated steadily since then, but mostly in recent years.
On the Facebook page of residents in the neighborhood, one resident says that the house has "not been particularly lively in recent years".
This may be due to the fact that the owners have wanted to change the house and the plot for several years.
Other neighbors say the house has not been in order for a long time.
“It’s long overdue to do something properly about this spot and it’s sad that it has taken so long.”
He also says that he is angry at the owners of the house for not hurrying to finish this, finding some common ground with the neighbors of the house and stopping this "legal mess".
“Just do this in consultation with the community around so we can hurry up and finish it.”
The “legal mess” that the resident refers to is the planning process for the site, which has been ongoing since at least 2017.
The owners of Dunhaga 18 and 20 then applied for permission to build a floor above the existing apartment building and behind the building, a new elevator house and an extension on one floor plus a basement.
The building permit granted for that project was appealed to the Appellate Board for Environmental and Resource Matters, and the board declared it null and void as the project was not supported by a zoning plan and the neighbourhood consultation was insufficient.
The City of Reykjavik then embarked on the zoning process and finished it with an announcement in the Official Gazette in July last year.
That plan was also appealed and the committee annulled it in March 2020.
At this point, nearly three years had passed since the initial application for a building permit and the owners of the house were just starting.
By this time, the house had deteriorated considerably and the neighbours were getting tired of it.
When DV asked the neighbors of the house about the situation and the reaction of the neighbors, the answers were in various ways.
Some people understood the intentions of the owners of the house, others did not at all.
Some directed their anger at the city, others did not.
Others were just angry, but not necessarily at anyone.
Others said the parking lots were a point of contention, but neighbours have used the unused parking lots at Dunhaga 18–20 for their vehicles.
One of the complainants in the case said he was tired of the administration:
“The fact that we have to go through the process three times is absolutely unbelievable.
It’s like the City of Reykjavik couldn’t read.”
Today the house is empty, abandoned and neglected.
A memorial to the fleeting administration of the city and the noble intentions of the owner and their many years of work that is now in its infancy.
When a journalist visited the garden at Dunhaga 18, he was struck by wide-open doors and piles of rubbish.
A Playstation and a new TV lay among other rubbish on the ground — victims of the icy summer rain.
There was an opening into the old office of Háskólaprents and there were a lot of cats, judging by the smell.
It is clear that someone has nested in one corner, but no one is visible.
Piles of couches and beds and a few pallets of geology papers, undoubtedly meant to become a book, came to mind.
The stairwells of the apartment building were also open and full of life.
A journalist was lucky enough to come across an inhabitant of one of them.
Some Romanians were cooking potatoes for dinner and invited a journalist in.
The Romanians work for the temporary employment agency Ztrongforce ehf.
They have been there for some time and DV sources say that the company has paid nothing for the premises except for heating and electricity.
Due to the condition of the building, it is not reasonable to charge rent.
From the post boxes in the lobby of the house it is clear that a number of foreign workers have lived there in recent years.
Temporary employment agencies have not been unaffected by the Covid-19 situation, as a decline in tourism has led to a decline in the construction sector, and these two industries have been the most active in using temporary employment agencies.
Nevertheless, the residents of Dunhaga 18 seemed to have plenty to do and hung their coats and mittens in the common area to dry after a long working day in the rain.
It should be noted that despite the poor condition of the house, the apartment that the boys shared seemed to be well maintained.
When a journalist said goodbye to the boys in Romanian, the irony suddenly became clear to him: In the best location in Reykjavík, a 1,500-square-meter property is dilapidated.
The owners want to change the house for the better and the neighbours want to improve the situation but disagree on the definition of “improvement”.
In between, the city’s planning department is sitting on the starting block, victim of endless appeals and appeals in the planning process and summary decisions of the Appeals Board on Environmental and Resource Issues.
Romanian workers live in the house, perhaps the ones who will improve the situation when the Icelanders stop arguing.
The article originally appeared in the weekly newspaper DV on 17 July.
