"Cooking is a kind of meditation" - See Elísa Vidar's menu
Elina Vidarsdóttir is an athlete in football and plays for Valur.
She is also a master’s student in nutrition, a mother, and works as a food scientist.
She needs a lot of energy for the hustle and bustle of the day and usually gives herself time to cook good and nutritious food.
A normal day for me starts with arriving at work at eight o’clock,” says Elísa.
“After work, I go to the grocery store so I can prepare dinner before I pick up my daughter at kindergarten around three o’clock.”
Elisa finds it very nourishing to pick up her daughter early in kindergarten.
“It’s good to have time with her before I go to practice in the afternoon.
After training, it’s nice to come home and just have to heat up the food.
At night, when the girl has fallen asleep, we like to watch one episode to clear our minds.”
Elisa doesn’t follow a specific diet.
She is finishing her master’s thesis in nutrition and therefore knows exactly what she needs to eat to have enough energy for work, school, family and exercise.
“What suits me is to eat a variety of foods that are well composed of proteins, carbohydrates and fats.
I think the most important thing is to have a healthy relationship with food and not classify food as bad or good, rather nutritious or non-nutritious.
It’s okay to eat everything, just not all at once and not always.”
Elisa is very interested in cooking.
“I find a certain meditation in standing in the kitchen cooking and therefore draw a lot from it.
I have to say that I feel confident in the kitchen and I sincerely believe that I am a good chef.”
Breakfast: Oats, chia seeds, hemp seeds, salt, a little lemon juice, soaked in almond milk overnight.
Top this meal with what is available at the time.
Usually it’s a banana and crispy muesli & COFFEE.
I'm a big coffee girl.
Snacks: Incredibly varied, but fruits or vegetables, flatbreads, plain skyr with bananas and muesli, bread with toppings and I could eat hummus with a spoon out of a box if necessary.
Lunch: I often make all kinds of nutritious salads from what I have in the fridge, quinoa or barley, falafel balls, rock salad, baked vegetables with a good dressing is a bit of what I am working with.
If the planning goes completely out of control (which happens a lot) then the egg machine at work has come to my rescue quite often and then it’s 2 slices of bread with butter, cheese and boiled egg, I’m not putting more on you.
Snacks: I eat something high in carbohydrates before training, bread with spreads, cereals or fruit.
Dinner: Fish is very often the choice in my home, otherwise some delicious vegetarian dishes.
