A new strain rather than a new type of virus
“A new virus just means that this has been an individual who came from abroad.
This is not something that has been simmering in Iceland,” says Már Kristjánsson, chief physician at the National Hospital’s Department of Infectious Diseases, about the news that a “new type of virus” has been detected in Iceland.
Three domestic cases were detected yesterday and two at the border.
One person who was diagnosed had participated in the social activities of a sports club at the Rey Cup football tournament, but the source of the infection has not been found and infection tracing is ongoing.
An infection was also detected in a person who came to Iceland on 15 July and two people who were in contact with him have started to show symptoms of COVID-19.
In addition, an infection was detected yesterday that is related to an infection reported the day before, and after sequencing at Icelandic Genomics, “a new type of virus that has not been detected here before” was revealed.
Tracing has been completed in connection with that infection.
Már points out that this is not a new virus, but rather the same virus that has spread around the world, i.e. the new coronavirus SARS-CoV-2.
It is more appropriate to speak of a new strain of that virus than of a new type of virus.
Asked what this means and whether it could mean that a second wave of the pandemic has begun, Már says that at the moment it is an isolated case and that it could turn out to be nothing more.
“On the other hand, if there are cases within Iceland that do not have links from abroad and have the same genotype as this particular variant, it would be possible to draw that conclusion [about a second wave], but it is premature at this point,” Már explains.
