On the steep to seek a hundred days in elections
There are 100 days until the Americans go to the polls to elect a president for a four-year term.
Donald Trump is running for re-election, but he has a steep path ahead of him.
Joe Biden, the prospective Democratic nominee, has a large lead over Trump at the national level, according to opinion polls.
According to a new poll by the AP news agency, a record number of Americans believe the nation is on the wrong track.
Trump’s response to the coronavirus pandemic is also very unpopular, and more Americans than before believe that the president has handled the economy poorly.
In fact, only two in ten Americans say the United States is on the right track.
32 percent say they support Trump’s response to the pandemic and 48 percent say he has managed the economy well.
In March that percentage was 56 percent and in January it was 67 percent.
According to FiveThirtyEight, Biden holds 49.9 percent of the national vote, while Trump holds 41.9 percent.
Trump himself has tried to shift attention away from his own performance in dealing with the pandemic to Biden, pushing for so-called cultural conflicts and advocating policies that are supposed to focus on law and order.
However, the Biden campaign is keen to keep the attention on Trump and believes it has a good chance of winning if the election is really about how Trump has performed in office over the past four years.
Trump's unpopularity also seems to be affecting Republican congressmen, and the Progressives fear that the Democrats could even achieve a majority in the US Senate, which so far has been considered very unlikely.
Politico recently reported that the Republican Party would suffer its worst defeat in decades if the party and candidate support remained comparable as it is now.
The outskirts proved particularly bad for the party in the 2016 parliamentary elections and it looks like that trend will continue.
In recent days, Trump has tried to intimidate suburban residents to follow him, among other things, by saying that if Biden becomes president, he will ruin the suburbs of the United States and push for racial divisions.
Among other things, Trump has repealed a regulation from the time of Barack Obama in the White House that was intended to increase diversity in the suburbs.
He then urged the "housewives" of the U.S. suburbs to read an article by a former assistant governor of New York, where she claimed that Biden would destroy the U.S. suburbs, and Trump agreed.
“Biden will destroy your neighborhoods and the American dream.
I will preserve it, and even make it better!” said the President.
Residents of the U.S. suburbs are an ever-growing group of voters.
According to NPR, they are about half of all voters in the United States.
Since George W. Bush's re-election in 2004, the candidate who has won the majority of this group's votes has been elected president.
Except in 2012 when Mitt Romney received the majority of votes from this group but lost to Barack Obama.
Opinion polls have shown that although Trump secured a narrow majority in the suburbs in 2016, his support there has shrunk significantly.
Although it varies between polls, Biden has shown a fifteen percentage point lead over Trump in recent outpouring.
