Will the Olympic flame be the light at the end of the tunnel?
After the final decision was made to postpone the Olympic Games, an event interrupted only by world wars, the President of the International Olympic Committee said that the famous Olympic torch would be “the light at the end of the tunnel,” presumably referring to the coronavirus pandemic that the world is now facing together.
Athletes have an additional year to prepare, and the Japanese government will reimburse the costs of the delay.
But everyone keeps their heads high, because there's a lot at stake.
When it was announced that Tokyo, Japan, would be the venue for this year’s Olympic Games, the celebrations of the Japanese delegates were genuine.
They laughed and cried, as Tokyo had applied to host the Games in 2016, but was defeated by Rio de Janeiro in Brazil.
This time, Tokyo and Japan were to bathe in the attention of the world.
The Games were originally scheduled to take place from 24 July to 9 August 2020, but were postponed to 23 July to 8 August 2021.
If the Games cannot be held then, if the coronavirus continues to be too much of a threat, the Games will be cancelled.
However, no one wants to think that thought to the end.
The Olympics are no ordinary sporting competition.
Nothing is spared, the show must always be spectacular and strive to top the last play.
The selection of a city for the Olympic Games is based on a selection committee's assessment of the cities' presentations.
The more spectacular the presentation, the greater the chance of winning the prize.
Tokyo spent $150 million on the bid to host the 2016 Olympic Games.
The second time, when applying for the 2020 Games, 75 million dollars, about ten billion crowns, were put into the application.
In 2013, when it was decided that Tokyo would host the Games, the Japanese authorities had already committed ISK 30 billion to the project.
But that amount is just a drop in the ocean compared to what it costs to build an Olympic village, stadiums and generally to strengthen the country's infrastructure to cope with such a tournament, prepare it and hold the games themselves.
Organizers in Japan have said the Tokyo Olympics, which were supposed to be running these days but have been postponed for a year due to the coronavirus, would have cost $12.6 billion.
However, a report by Japan’s National Audit Office, published at the end of last year, suggested that the cost was more than twice that figure.
The cost of postponing the Games is unlikely to be fully assessed, but it has been estimated that it could cost between $2 billion and $6 billion in addition to the original cost.
The total cost for the Japanese Olympic Committee and Japanese taxpayers could therefore range from $ 15 billion to $ 30 billion.
These figures are so high that all tax revenue of the Icelandic state would only be enough for about half the Olympic Games, based on the lowest possible cost.
The Olympic Games are an event of such magnitude that they have become the subject of economics, which tries to analyze the numbers and examine the benefits and benefits of the games.
In short, quite a few people seem to have come to the conclusion that the impact of the Olympic Games is less than positive for the economies of the cities that host them.
The short-term effects are some, for example, there is a huge increase in jobs in the short term, but in the longer term, cities tend to be left with debt and high operating costs of underutilized infrastructure.
Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, is in considerable debt from the 2016 Games and has been struggling to pay for the maintenance of all the major sports facilities built for the Games.
A review of figures after the London 2012 Olympics revealed that only 10 per cent of those employed during the Olympics were previously unemployed.
This means that no new jobs were created except to a small extent.
In general, cities have not fared particularly well financially hosting the Olympic Games due to the overwhelming costs associated with the infrastructure built for the Games.
However, benefits are often attributed to the increased number of tourists wishing to visit the Olympic cities following the Games, although there is a great deal of uncertainty regarding the 2021 Games.
It is also uncertain whether it will be possible to accommodate the full number of spectators that normally attend the Games.
The most important thing, however, is the honour of being chosen, which is difficult to measure in monetary terms.
Because despite the huge costs, it can also be said that the joy that the Games bring is not of a nature that can be priced.
But although the exhibition is often grandiose and no expense is spared, it is of course not just about money.
It is the sports heroes who are in the foreground.
For some athletes, the postponement of the Games is a welcome surprise.
The Australian pentathlete and gold medalist in her event at the last Olympic Games, Chloe Esposito, for example, is pregnant and would have been away from good fun this summer, but she is hoping to be in competitive form for the 2021 Games.
She is therefore among those athletes who is just rather happy with the postponement, for understandable reasons.
For those athletes who intended to retire after this year's Games, if they had been held on time, the postponement of the Games in some cases means they will retire before the Games take place.
Trust their body simply not in order to go through extra years of rigorous exercises.
Few athletes have captured the hearts of spectators at the Rio 2016 Olympic Games like gymnastics star Simone Biles.
She came home with four gold medals and one bronze.
Biles has appeared in several interviews in her home country of the United States recently to discuss the Olympics.
She plans to participate in the 2021 Games, but she is not necessarily sure that she will still be at the top at the Games next year, because she will be 24 years old by then.
Although it is not generally considered high age, it is in the upper range for a gymnast of the first rank.
“It’s a sensitive issue,” said Biles, smiling in an interview published on the Olympic Committee’s Instagram page, when asked if she intends to reach as far at the 2021 Games as she did in Rio 2016.
“I just don’t know if I’ll still be at the top after another year of training,” says Biles.
She has previously talked about her body not being able to withstand the strain of gymnastics much longer.
Nevertheless, she is training hard for the 2021 Olympic Games.
Biles admits that it was an uncomfortable feeling to have to suddenly stop practicing at the height of the pandemic and the gymnasium was closed.
No exceptions were made for Biles or anyone else while all sports facilities were closed for seven weeks.
All her Olympic gold could not buy any access above the others, she had to find various ways to keep herself in shape like others.
The basic form certainly slightly better than most people.
“We have a tight schedule now.
It was hard to start practicing again after the gymnasium opened.
We started slowly but we are back on track and I will increase the training steadily as the year goes on.
Of course, we do not know exactly how these games will be or whether they will be held, but we are still practicing for them, we can not do otherwise.
I’ve worked too hard to leave the sport now,” Biles said.
Like many others, she has her doubts, or rather her awareness of the possibility that the Games will not be held in 2021 either.
To predict that, however, is hopeless.
No one can know how the situation of the coronavirus pandemic will be in July 2021, and there is nothing else to do but to prepare for the Olympics given that they will be held next year.
Maybe the Olympic flame will be the light at the end of the Covid marches.
Postponed wedding due to pandemic
Modern Family actress Sarah Hyland has decided to postpone her wedding due to the coronavirus.
She was supposed to marry former Bachelorette contestant Wells Adams this summer.
“I think there are other more important things to think about right now,” the actress told People.
“We definitely want to get married one day and have the wedding of our dreams with all the people who are dear to us.
But we decided to postpone it and focus on what is important right now, which is to help share information about the importance of wearing masks and staying at home.
I'm more interested in world affairs than weddings these days.
There’s a lot going on and we need to focus our attention on what’s happening in the world.”
